The aim of this notebook is to make use of the word2vec model to find similar songs

To train the word2vec model, we first need to build its vocabulary. To do that, I iterated over each song and added it to an array that can later be fed to the model.

  • Se van a reemplazar todas los signos de puntuacin y acentos para que no las cuente como palabras distintas. Adems, eliminamos la palabra estribillo y x2 ya que no son propias de la letra de la cancin.

In [11]:
text_corpus = []
for song in songs['letra']:
    song = song.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    song = song.lower()
    song = re.sub('(||estribillo|x2)','',song)
    words = song.split()
    text_corpus.append(words)

# Dimensionality of the resulting word vectors.
#more dimensions, more computationally expensive to train
#but also more accurate
#more dimensions = more generalized
num_features = 50
# Minimum word count threshold.
min_word_count = 1

# Number of threads to run in parallel.
#more workers, faster we train
num_workers = multiprocessing.cpu_count()

# Context window length.
context_size = 7

downsampling = 1e-1

In [20]:
# Seed for the RNG, to make the results reproducible.
#random number generator
#deterministic, good for debugging
seed = 1

songs2vec = w2v.Word2Vec(
    sg=1,
    seed=seed,
    workers=num_workers,
    size=num_features,
    min_count=min_word_count,
    window=context_size,
    sample=downsampling
)

songs2vec.build_vocab(text_corpus)
print(len(text_corpus))

9325

In [22]:
import time
start_time = time.time() 

songs2vec.train(text_corpus, total_examples=songs2vec.corpus_count, epochs=2)

if not os.path.exists("trained"):
    os.makedirs("trained")

songs2vec.save(os.path.join("trained", "songs2vectors.w2v"))

print("--- %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

--- 43.290398836135864 seconds ---

Semantic distance between words

In [34]:
def nearest_similarity_cosmul(start1, end1, end2):
    similarities = songs2vec.wv.most_similar_cosmul(
        positive=[end2, start1],
        negative=[end1]
    )
    start2 = similarities[0][0]
    print("{0} es a {1}, lo que {2} es a {3}".format(start1, end1, start2, end2))
In [38]:
nearest_similarity_cosmul("amor", "novio", "amigo")

amor es a novio, lo que odio es a amigo

# Seed for the RNG, to make the results reproducible.
#random number generator
#deterministic, good for debugging
seed = 1
num_features = 100
window = 5 #10

songs2vec = w2v.Word2Vec(
    sg=1,
    seed=seed,
    workers=num_workers,
    size=num_features, #Tamap del vector denso para representar cada palabra
    min_count=min_word_count,
    window=context_size, #distancia mxima del contexto. Ventana ms pequea, elementos ms relacionados
    sample=downsampling
)

songs2vec.build_vocab(text_corpus)

To train the word2vec model, we first need to build its vocabulary. To do that, I iterated over each song and added it to an array that can later be fed to the model.

In [72]:
datos = data['The Project Gutenberg EBook of Don Quijote, by Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra']
In [73]:
text_corpus2 = []
contar = 0
parrafos=[]
for line in datos:
    line = line.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    line = re.sub('(||)','',line)
    words = line.lower().split()
    parrafos.extend(words)
    contar+=1
    if contar == 20:
        contar = 0
        parrafos = []
        text_corpus2.append(parrafos)

downsampling = 1e-1

# Seed for the RNG, to make the results reproducible.
#random number generator
#deterministic, good for debugging
seed = 1
num_features = 50
window = 10 #10

text2vec = w2v.Word2Vec(
    sg=1,
    seed=seed,
    workers=num_workers,
    size=num_features, #Tamao del vector denso para representar cada palabra
    min_count=min_word_count,
    window=context_size, #distancia mxima del contexto. Ventana ms pequea, elementos ms relacionados
    sample=downsampling
)

text2vec.build_vocab(text_corpus2)
print(len(text_corpus2))

Semantic distance between words

In [86]:
def nearest_similarity_cosmul(start1, end1, end2):
    similarities = text2vec.wv.most_similar_cosmul(
        positive=[end2, start1],
        negative=[end1]
    )
    start2 = similarities[0][0]
    print("{0} es a {1}, lo que {2} es a {3}".format(start1, end1, start2, end2))
  • En el Quijote:
In [87]:
nearest_similarity_cosmul("amor", "pareja", "amigo")

amor es a pareja, lo que hijo es a amigo
In [88]:
nearest_similarity_cosmul("dulcinea", "quijote", "sancho")

dulcinea es a quijote, lo que seora es a sancho

In [79]:
def songVector(row):
    vector_sum = 0
    row = row.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    row = row.lower()
    row = re.sub('(||estribillo|x2)','',row)
    words = row.split()
    for word in words:
        vector_sum = vector_sum + songs2vec[word]
    vector_sum = vector_sum.reshape(1,-1)
    normalised_vector_sum = sklearn.preprocessing.normalize(vector_sum)
    return normalised_vector_sum

t-sne and random song selection

The songs have 100 dimensions each. Application of t-sne is memory intensive and hence it is slightly easier on the computer to use a random sample of the 57,000 songs.

In [82]:

train, test = train_test_split(songs, test_size = 0.9)


for song_vector in train['song_vector']:
    song_vectors.append(song_vector)

I had a fairly measly 4gb machine and wasn't able to generate a more accurate model. However, one can play around with the number of iterations, learning rate and other factors to fit the model better. If you have too many dimensions (~300+), it might make sense to use PCA first and then t-sne.

Plotting the results

Using plotly, I plotted the results so that it becomes easier to explore similar songs based on their colors and clusters.

In [92]:
from plotly.offline import download_plotlyjs, init_notebook_mode, plot, iplot

init_notebook_mode(connected=True)

import plotly.graph_objs as go

trace1 = go.Scatter(
    y = two_dimensional_songs['Y'],
    x = two_dimensional_songs['X'],
    text = two_dimensional_songs['cancion'],
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(
        size= 5,#'7',
        color = np.random.randn(5717), #set color equal to a variable
        colorscale='Viridis',
        showscale=True
    )
)
data = [trace1]

iplot(data)

Podemos ver que para los artistas dibujados, las canciones de Rayden vemos que son similares, ya que se mentienen por la misma zona, en cambio, viendo a Fyahbwoy vemos que sus canciones estn en posiciones alejadas unas de otras, por lo que resalta una cancin que no es nada parecida a las otras. Luego Beret tiene letras parecidas a las canciones que escribe Rayden. Kase O es parecido a Fyahbwoy, adems tiene una cancin que es la que ms visitas tiene con diferencia.

from plotly.offline import download_plotlyjs, init_notebook_mode, plot, iplot

init_notebook_mode(connected=True)

import plotly.graph_objs as go

fig = go.Scatter(
    x = two_dimensional_songs['X'],
    y = two_dimensional_songs['Y'],
    text = 'Artista: ' + two_dimensional_songs['artista']+ " - Cancion: "+two_dimensional_songs['cancion'],
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(
        size= 5,#'7',

        showscale=True
    )
)

fig = [fig]
iplot(fig)

Viendo este grfico podemos ver que casi todas las canciones de los artistas rondan las 10,000~20,000 visualizaciones. Por tratarse del mismo gnero musical, las canciones son similares entre los artistas, exceptuando dos que se alejan mucho del centro Capaz y Sharif

import plotly.graph_objects as go
import numpy as np

fig = go.Figure(data=go.Scatter(
    x = dataf['X'],
    y = dataf['Y'],
    text = 'Artista: ' + dataf['artista']+ " - Cancion: "+dataf['cancion'],
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(
        size=16,
        color=dataf['visitas'], #set color equal to a variable
        colorscale='Viridis', # one of plotly colorscales
        showscale=True
    )
))

fig.show()

import plotly.express as px

fig = px.scatter_3d(dataf, x = 'X', y = 'Y', z='visitas', color='artista')
fig.show()
  • En este grfico podemos ver que el nmero de visitas es un poco independiente del artista, y ms dependiente de la cancin en si, adems, los artistas tienen canciones que son muy similares entre s y entre ellas. Pero como son del mismo estilo no hay grupos definidos en funcin del artista, si no que relacionan ms las canciones en s.
